\layout Section


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Introduction}

\end_inset 

Introduction
\layout Standard

The detection of transient phenomena, with time-scales ranging from less
 than a second up to weeks or months, is one of the Key Science Areas of
 LOFAR.
 
\emph on 
(Hours, days, minutes, seconds, sub-sec (exclude pulsars).
 Bright (dominating) and faint transients.)
\layout Standard

Obviously, transients should be detected in the image-plane, where the S/N
 is maximised because all information about a source is concentrated in
 a small nr of pixels.
 By contrast, each uv-sample contains information about 
\emph on 
all
\emph default 
 sources in the FOV, which is much more difficult to sort out.
\layout Standard

Perhaps because of this, the transient detection techniques that have been
 proposed for LOFAR concentrate on image analysis.
 Snapshots of uv-data are to be calibrated, transformed into images, deconvolved
, and compared with each other.
 
\layout Standard

The problem with this approach is that LOFAR calibration will require a
 lot of processing.
 Apart from dealing with a rapidly varying ionosphere and 'wobbly' station
 voltage beams, it is necessary to subtract most sources in the uv-plane.
 The latter is necessary because residual image-plane effects, i.e.
 instrumental effects that vary over the FOV, cause the Point Spread Function
 (PSF) with which the sources are convolved in the image, to be position-depende
nt as well.
 This violates the assumption of deconvolution techniques like CLEAN.
\layout Standard

This provides an incentive to look for other possibilities.
 This document proposes a differential method, in which successive uv-data
 samples of the same interferometer are subtracted from each other.
 The idea is to remove all sources that do not change, thus emphasizing
 the transient phenomena.
 The great advantage is that we do not have to remove the constant sources
 by means of deconvolution.
 This saves a lot of processing, while the subtraction, and thus the sensitivity
 for transient detection, is (a lot) better.
 Also, we can get away with a minimum of calibration, because instrumental
 errors change much more slowly than the subtraction interval of 1-10 s.
 
\series bold 
It will be demonstrated that such a short interval is sufficient to detect
 transient phenomena with a much wider range of time-scales
\series default 
.
 A third advantage is that we do not need to generate and analyse a different
 set of images for each transient time-scale.
\layout Standard

An obvious limitation of such a differential method is that the Earth rotates,
 so that the uv-coordinates will change between successive samples.
 This will affect the subtraction accuracy, especially for sources further
 from the field centre, and for longer baselines.
 However, it will be seen that the actual numbers come out surprisingly
 well, and that there are a variety of additional tricks that can be brought
 to bear to make them even better
\begin_inset Foot
collapsed true

\layout Standard

In fact, the numbers come out so well that it is surprising that this approach
 has not been tried before.
 An uncomfortable thought, whichever way one looks at it.....
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The proposed method will be analysed and demonstrated for the WSRT case.
 However, the results are equally valid for LOFAR and other telescopes.
\layout Section


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Corrugations-in-the}

\end_inset 

Corrugations in the uv-plane
\layout Standard

The visibility function is the sum of the contributions of all the sources
 in the field.
 Ignoring the w-coordinate for the moment, we can write:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
V(u,v)=\sum_{k}p_{k}exp(2\pi i(ul_{k}+vm_{k}))+noise\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The contribution of a point source is a sinusoidal corrugation in the uv-plane,
 with amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}$
\end_inset 

, and a period and orientation that depend only on the source position 
\begin_inset Formula $(l_{k},m_{k})$
\end_inset 

.
 The period is inversely proportional to the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k}=\sqrt{l_{k}^{2}+m_{k}^{2}}\;(rad)$
\end_inset 

 to the field centre, and the orientation of the corrugation ridges is parallel
 to the line 
\begin_inset Formula $(ul_{k}+vm_{k})=0$
\end_inset 

.
 See fig 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:The-contribution-to}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The visibility function is sampled with one or more interferometers, each
 consisting of a pair of telescopes, or stations, 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

.
 The uv-coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(u(t),v(t))$
\end_inset 

 of a sample 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{ij}(t)$
\end_inset 

 depend on the length and orientation of the (projected) baseline between
 the stations, as seen from the source.
 As the Earth rotates, an interferometer samples the visibility function
 along an ellipsoidal track in the uv-plane, with a 'velocity' that is proportio
nal to baseline length.
 
\layout Standard

Ignoring noise, we may write:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
V_{ij}(t)=\sum_{k}V_{ijk}(t)=\sum_{k}p_{k}\exp^{i\theta_{k}(t)}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

where
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\theta_{k}(t)=2\pi\frac{b}{\lambda}(l_{k}cosHA(t)+m_{k}sinHA(t).sinDEC)\label{eq:theta(t)}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

We also need the rate of change of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(t)$
\end_inset 

:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{d\theta(t)}{dt}=2\pi\frac{b}{\lambda}(-l_{k}\sin HA(t)+m_{k}\cos HA(t).\sin DEC).\frac{dHA}{dt}\label{eq:dtheta/dt}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

and the second derivative (noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dHA}{dt}$
\end_inset 

 is constant):
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{d^{2}\theta(t)}{dt^{2}}=-2\pi\frac{b}{\lambda}(l_{k}\cos HA(t)+m_{k}\sin HA(t).\sin DEC).\frac{dHA}{dt}=-\theta(t).\frac{dHA}{dt}\label{eq:d2theta/dt2}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

A very important quantity is the (constant) rate of change of the baseline
 Hour Angle (HA) due to Earth rotation.
 Using the familiar value of 15 deg/hr, or 
\begin_inset Formula $1/240$
\end_inset 

 deg/s, we get:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{dHA}{dt}=\frac{\Delta HA}{\Delta t}=\frac{1}{240*57}=0.73\times10^{-4}\; rad/s\label{eq: dHA/dt}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Note also that this constant rate of change in HA will result in a smaller
 sampling 'velocity', i.e.
 samples that are closer together, near the centre of the uv-plane.
 
\layout Standard


