\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Subtracting-successive-uv-data}

\end_inset 

Subtracting successive uv-data
\layout Standard

We propose to detect transient sources by comparing successive uv-samples
 of the same interferometer.
 Since the uv-coordinates, and thus the phase factors 
\begin_inset Formula $(u(t).l_{k}+v(t).m_{k})$
\end_inset 

 will be slightly different due to Earth rotation, there will be a subtraction
 error.
 The latter may be minimised by subtracting the average of the uv-samples
 before and after:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Delta V_{ij}(t)=V_{ij}(t)-\frac{1}{2}(V_{ij}(t+\Delta t)+V_{ij}(t-\Delta t))\label{eq:dVij}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

This approach has the additional advantage that instrumental errors that
 change linearly with time are also compensated (see section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sec:Instrumental-errors}

\end_inset 

).
 
\layout Standard

Since everything is linear, we may analyse the problem per source 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

, i.e.
 we may calculate the subtraction error as a function of source position
 
\begin_inset Formula $(l_{k},m_{k})$
\end_inset 

.
 From fig 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:The-contribution-to}

\end_inset 

 it is easily seen that the subtraction error is smaller if the visibility
 corrugation of a particular source has a longer period, i.e.
 for shorter baselines or sources closer to the field centre.
 Thus, when making an image of the differences, subtraction residuals will
 be larger for the (non-transient) sources further from the centre.
 
\layout Standard

The subtraction error for source 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

 is:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Delta V_{ijk}(t)=p_{k}(\exp^{i\theta_{k}(t)}-\frac{1}{2}(\exp^{i\theta_{k}(t+\Delta t)}+\exp^{i\theta_{k}(t-\Delta t)}))\label{eq:dVijk}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Using the property 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\exp^{i\alpha}-\frac{1}{2}(\exp^{i(\alpha+\epsilon)}+\exp^{i(\alpha-\epsilon)})=\exp^{i\alpha}(1-\cos\epsilon)\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

we find that, provided we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(t\pm\Delta t)$
\end_inset 

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(t)\pm\epsilon(\Delta t)$
\end_inset 

, we may derive a 
\emph on 
subtraction error factor
\emph default 
 
\begin_inset Formula $1-cos(\epsilon)$
\end_inset 

.
 Fortunately, this turns out to be possible for our particular function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(t)=A.cosHA(t)+B.sinHA(t)$
\end_inset 

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta HA=0.73\times10^{-4}\Delta t$
\end_inset 

 is small:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\theta(t\pm\Delta HA)=\theta(t).\cos(\Delta HA)\pm\frac{d\theta(t)}{dt}\sin(\Delta HA)\approx\theta(t)\pm0.73\times10^{-4}\frac{d\theta(t)}{dt}\Delta t\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The 
\emph on 
error factor
\emph default 
 gives the residual of source 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

 in the samples of ifr 
\begin_inset Formula $ij$
\end_inset 

, as a fraction of the source flux 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{k}$
\end_inset 

: 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
errfac_{ijk}(\Delta t)=1-\cos(\epsilon_{ijk})\approx\frac{1}{2}\epsilon_{ijk}^{2}\label{eq: errfac(ijk)}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

in which (using equ 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dtheta/dt}

\end_inset 

)
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\epsilon_{ijk}(\Delta t)=abs(0.73\times10^{-4}\frac{d\theta}{dt}\Delta t)\;\leq\;2\pi\times0.73\times10^{-4}\frac{b_{ij}}{\lambda}r_{k}\Delta t\; rad\label{eq: epsilon}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

For convenience, the term within brackets of equ 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:dtheta/dt}

\end_inset 

 has been replaced with the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k}$
\end_inset 

(rad) of a source 
\begin_inset Formula $(l_{k},m_{k})$
\end_inset 

 from the field centre.
 Note that this always overestimates the subtraction error.
\layout Standard


\series bold 
The numbers work out surprisingly well.

\series default 
 If we take baseline 
\begin_inset Formula $b=2$
\end_inset 

 km and wavelength 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=2$
\end_inset 

 m (i.e.
 the WSRT or the LOFAR core), 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t=1s$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k}=0.1$
\end_inset 

 rad (5 deg!), the error factor is 
\begin_inset Formula $<0.01$
\end_inset 

 for all visibilities.
 See also fig 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:The-error-factor}

\end_inset 

.
 In reality, the numbers will be even better, since equ 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq: epsilon}

\end_inset 

 consistently over-estimates the subtraction error, and the 
\emph on 
average
\emph default 
 baseline will be rather smaller than 2 km.
 However, the sidelobes of poorly subtracted point sources far from the
 field centre will limit the transient detection performance, and we should
 try to minimise them.
 This is the subject of the next section.
\layout Standard


