The contribution to the visibility function of a point source at position
 
\begin_inset Formula $(l_{k},m_{k})$
\end_inset 

 is a sinusoidal corrugation in the uv-plane.
 Its period is inversely proportional to the baseline length, and the distance
 of the source from the field centre.
 Successive samples of a particular interferometer sample these sinusoids
 at points 
\begin_inset Formula $t-dt,t,t+dt,...$
\end_inset 

etc, which will be closer to each other near the centre of the uv-plane.
 Short-term transients, with a time-scale of 1-500 seconds, may be detected
 by subtracting from each sample 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 the average of the two adjacent samples 
\begin_inset Formula $t-dt$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t+dt$
\end_inset 

, and making an image of the residuals.
 This removes the sources that do not vary in time, leaving only the transient
 ones.
 Obviously, the subtraction error will increase as 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset 

 is a larger fraction of the corrugation period.
 Therefore, sources close to the field centre, or extended sources that
 are only visible to short baselines, will be subtracted more completely.
\end_inset 


\layout Section

Variable sources
\layout Standard

We have demonstrated that sources are can be subtracted (filtered) pretty
 effectively, depending on their position 
\begin_inset Formula $(l_{k},m_{k})$
\end_inset 

 w.r.t.
 the field centre.
 We will now investigate what happens with time-variable sources, i.e.
 sources with a flux that varies linearly in time:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\Delta V_{ijk}(t)=p_{k}\exp^{i\theta(t)}-\frac{1}{2}((p_{k}+\Delta p_{k})\exp^{i\theta(t+\Delta t)}-(p_{k}-\Delta p_{k})\exp^{i\theta(t-\Delta t)})\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

A little algebra then leads to:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\Delta V_{ijk}(t)=p_{k}\exp^{i\theta(t)}(1-\cos(\epsilon)-i\frac{\Delta p_{k}}{p_{k}}\sin(\epsilon))\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset 

 has the same meaning as in equ 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq: epsilon}

\end_inset 

, of course.
 Thus, the time-varying part of a source may be distinguised in principle
 from the constant part because the latter forms a residual peak at its
 position, while the former would produce a ring around the position (multiplica
tion by 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset 

 causes a shift of the fringe by 90 deg).
 Unfortunately, since 
\begin_inset Formula $sin(\epsilon)$
\end_inset 

 changes sign rapidly, the ring will be averaged out, unless we use selected
 uv-samples only (i.e.
 only those that add up constructively).
 This can be done in principle, but the selection will be different for
 different parts of the image w.r.t.
 the centre, and for different baselines.
\layout Standard

In any case, transients can only be detected for thos sources that are not
 subtracted completely.....
\layout Standard

The situation is different for sources who's flux varies non-linearly in
 time....
\layout Section


\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sec:Limiting-the-FOV}

\end_inset 

Limiting the FOV
\layout Standard

As we have seen, the subtraction is most effective for sources close to
 the field centre (small l,m), and/or small baseline length (small u,v).
 This means that sources outside a certain radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{max}$
\end_inset 

 will not be subtracted very well.
 The sidelobes of those residuals could be a severe limitation to the sensitivit
y of our transient detection scheme.
 However, it is possible to attenuate them by integrating the uv-differences
 over freq and time, thereby effectively reducing the FOV.
 This is done independently for each facet, after shifting the uv-residuals
 to the facet centre.
 
\layout Standard

When averaging uv-data over a certain time or freq interval, the facet image
 is multplied by a sinc function.
 Since we only want to attenuate the sources outside the facet, we require
 that the first zero 
\begin_inset Formula $(sinc(\pi))$
\end_inset 

 lies at 
\begin_inset Formula $2*r_{max}$
\end_inset 

.
 In adddition, the averaging function has to be tapered in such a way that
 the sidelobes of the sinc function die out rapidly.
\layout Standard

For 
\series bold 
frequency averaging
\series default 
 over a wavelength interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\lambda$
\end_inset 

, we require
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
2\pi b(\frac{1}{\lambda_{1}}-\frac{1}{\lambda_{2}}).r_{max}=2\pi\frac{b}{\lambda}\frac{\Delta\lambda}{\lambda}.r_{max}=2\pi\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

or, with 
\begin_inset Formula $b/\lambda=1000$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{max}$
\end_inset 

 in deg (
\begin_inset Formula $r_{max}=R_{max}/57$
\end_inset 

):
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta\lambda}{\lambda}=\frac{0.06}{R_{max}}\label{eq:fractional_lambda}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

This amount of fractional bandwidth easy to achieve, certainly for LOFAR,
 where a fractional bandwidth of up to 0.1 will be available.
\layout Standard

Unfortunately, things are not as straightforward for 
\series bold 
time averaging
\series default 
.
 Like above, we require:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
2\pi0.73\times10^{-4}\frac{b}{\lambda}\Delta t.r_{max}=2\pi\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

or, with 
\begin_inset Formula $b/\lambda=1000$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{max}$
\end_inset 

 in deg:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Delta t=\frac{780}{R_{max}}\label{eq: time_averaging}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

