Transient detection
\layout Standard

We are now ready to discuss how to detect transient sources with the proposed
 uv-subtraction method.
 The first step is to make residual images from residual uv-data: 
\layout Itemize

Correct the uv-data for ionospheric phase variations (in the direction of
 the field centre).
 See below.
\layout Itemize

Do the subtraction (equ ...), and produce residual uv-data.
 The subtraction interval is equal to the uv-data integration time (10 s
 for WSRT, and 1 s for LOFAR).
 (indicate how to deal with flags and edge effects)
\layout Itemize

Make residual facet images.
 For each facet, move the phase centre to the facet centre, correct the
 residual uv-data for the facet centre (...?), and integrate over an optimum
 nr of frequency channels to limit the FOV.
 Then FFT.
 
\layout Standard

The above will be part of the regular LOFAR operation scheme.
 The more interesting part, to be undertaken by the Key Science Group, is
 the analysis of residual images:
\layout Itemize

The source residuals at positions 
\begin_inset Formula $(l_{k},m_{k})$
\end_inset 

 will be point-like, because short baselines are subtracted much more effectivel
y than longer ones, and because transients are point sources by definition.
 
\layout Itemize

The source residuals are the sum of a constant and a transient part (the
 latter will often be zero, of course).
 These are convolved with with different PSF's.
 
\series bold 
Ignoring instrumental errors for the moment:
\begin_deeper 
\layout Itemize

The PSF of the constant part is position-dependent, and predictable (....?).
 See equ ...
 and fig ...
\layout Itemize

The PSF of the transient part depends on its time-profile.
 
\end_deeper 
\layout Itemize

Since the PSF of the constant part is predictable, and quite distinct (...)
 from the PSF of the transient part, we can try to deconvolve the residual
 image.
 On the one hand this is simple, because the residual sources are point
 sources.
 But it does require the calculation of a separate PSF for the position
 
\begin_inset Formula $(l_{k},m_{k})$
\end_inset 

 of each source.
 
\emph on 
And there is the problem of instrumetal errors, which affect the shape of
 the PSF.
\layout Itemize

Confusion between the two PSF's may be resolved by repeating the subtraction
 for two or more different phase centres.
 This changes the PSF of the constant residual (in a predictable way) but
 not the PSF of the transient.
 
